Defendant Louis J Johnson in court with attorney Stephen Andrew Sargent.  Defendant Louis J Johnson in custody.  Sara Nicole Volden Schroeder appeared on behalf of DeAnn L. Heard for the State of Wisconsin.  Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  The Court imposed the following sentence:

AS TO COUNT 01:
The Court imposed 6 months at the House of Correction, consecutive to any other sentence, and placed defendant on probation for one (1) year, concurrent to the probation ordered in Count 2.

AS TO COUNT 02:
Defendant's TOTAL LENGTH OF SENTENCE shall be 5 years.  Defendant's TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin Prison System shall be for 2-1/2 years with credit for 123 days time served.  Defendant shall serve 2-1/2 years on EXTENDED SUPERVISION.    The defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.  The Court advised the defendant of his determinate sentence pursuant to statute and in accordance with Form CR-234.  Copy provided to defendant.   The Court STAYED THE SENTENCE and placed the defendant on probation to the State Department of Corrections for a period of three (3) years probation.
 * Court ordered defendant to provide a DNA sample, if not previously taken.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION (and Extended Supervision, if revoked) AS TO COUNTS 1 AND 2:
 - Serve one (1) year condition time at the House of Correction with release to the Day Reporting Center; good time allowed;
 - No contact with  Valayshia C., her residence or workplace;
 - No contact with Scott H.;
 - Undergo a mental health evaluation; follow any treatment recommended;
 - No controlled substances other than those legally prescribed for defendant by a duly licensed physician for his mental or physical needs; take as prescribed and for only as long as deemed medically reasonable and necessary;
 - No alcohol;
 - AODA assessment; treatment if needed;
 - Urine screens;
 - Obtain GED;
 - Anger management counseling;
 - Seek and maintain employment;
 - Be given job and vocational training;
 - Cognitive thinking intervention counseling;
  - Pay the DNA surcharges, costs, and disbursements as ordered.  Failure to pay amounts in full would result in a civil judgment entered against defendant.  Should defendant get revoked and be sent to prison, Court ordered monies to be taken by the Department of Corrections from up to 25% of prison funds.  Balance to then be paid while on Extended Supervision.

Court set restitution at zero, as none has been requested.

